column1: Between 16 October 2020 and 31 December 2021, how many successful flight tests of the Common Hypersonic Glide Body (C-HGB) will the United States conduct?
column6: ['Technology', 'Security and Conflict']
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_hY3-uEu0IU

As of the date of my posting, the device has been successfully tested twice. The current schedule seems to be about three tests a year, though weather and logistics likely forbid testing in the remaining weeks of this year. Three to four tests are likely next year.

We are certainly testing but the question of being announced is a different story. Given the situation in eastern europe and peacocking with China and Olympics I don't believe current administration would have the tenacity to be so bold.
U.S still not ready but eager
If it hasn’t happened by now, I believe the likelihood of it happening by the end of the year is slim enough to be considered zero.

Plans were made for another Air Force test to be done in Q3 of 2021, but that deadline came and went. Likelihood of 4 successful test taking place in the next 28 days is slim. It is possible, however, that successful tests could take place, or have already taken place, and the announcement about them just hasn't been made yet. Given that, I chose the percentages I did.

Looks like plans for three tests, with one past one having been successful. So seems no chance of four tests, and it's very unlikely that none of the planned three would be successful. Seems better than even chance that future tests will be successful, given past success, and roughly even chance, given that, that either one or two instead fail.
These flights were mentioned in the press a few weeks ago
Big thanks to @Ryan-Beck for the article he linked to. I'm adjusting my forecast accordingly.

I'm switching to favor zero. I'm basing that on time remaining and also the fact that in this interview published yesterday General Thurgood was asked if they're still on track to test the CHGB by the end of the year and he kind of dodged it by saying 3 tests in FY 2022. Doesn't inspire confidence to me, I think if they were on track for that he would have wanted to call attention to that. Leaving plenty of probability on one currently because it's possible the military doesn't like to tie that down in advance for security reasons.

Since the test on Oct 21 failed the DoD will likely do root cause analysis to reduce the chance of another failure. This can be a long process and then a fix would have to be implemented. Plus the friction of the holidays is upon us slowing work more. Even with a different booster the irrational risk averse DoD is unlikely to conduct another test within 12 months. https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/42837/new-u-s-long-range-hypersonic-weapon-test-fails-updated
Very recent test. Next appear to be planned for first q of next fy. Delays in manufacturing. Only Arrw.
https://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/smd/2021/08/11/next-flight-test-of-hypersonic-glide-body-expected-by-years-end/
Going up 5 on zero, there have been multiple delays already. Though the Chinese hypersonic weapon test may light a fire under the US testing program.
https://edition.cnn.com/2021/10/21/politics/us-hypersonic-test-fails/index.html April was the last one. Doesn't seam to have enough time to study this failure and make another one.
Decided I should expand the tail a bit since very little info is publicly available.
https://youtu.be/h0pDDUjqniQ
Thank you Mr. @Ryan-Beck for the update
Significant downgrade based on the article quoted by @Ryan-Beck (thank you). Seems 3 would be optimistic, although still fully 4 1/2 months of the year left so not totally ruling it out.

Yep this confirms it, only one test planned this year, they canceled the test that was supposed to happen recently. Still possible this test could test 2 missiles at once or something, but a result of 3 is probably ruled out entirely. Very possible they miss their window for the next test too.
Another search, another complete lack of information on progress or any successful testing happening. Skewing down even more.
Hedging toward crowd
I've found a report from some misc. US military news site titled "Conventional Prompt Global Strike and Long-Range Ballistic Missiles: Background and Issues" (1).

This question poses some questions. As written it says: " A flight test will be considered “successful” if the U.S. military announces that the C-HGB reaches its designated impact point (Defense News)." So ... what happens if the US Military announces that it hit within 6 inches of the target, which is what happened in the first test? That's not "reaching the designated impact point", right? Anyway, I'm going to assume that ether: a) blasting the designated impact point to smithereens; or b) the US military announcing that the test was a success will count as a success.

-33 on 3. The Navy announced that they tested the first stage of the Solid Rocket Motor (SRM) which will be used with the hypersonic glide body. But the release definitely makes it sound like this is distinct from the hypersonic glide body itself, and also the release says the following:
There are supposed to be two events scheduled, the first has one test and the second two.
https://www.defensenews.com/pentagon/2021/03/23/ambitious-flight-test-schedule-for-hypersonic-weapons-at-risk/

My forecast is based on will the USAF announce. Probably already done. The USAF is a military organization that has a culture of using technology it engineers and fields. They don’t lie to the public but they have a history of “it’s none of your business because it’s classified”.

A good background article about the hype(rsonics) in the US, Russia, China, strengths and weaknesses of the concept over ICBM etc. "The Pentagon’s 2021 budget request for hypersonic-related research was US$3.2 billion – up from US$2.6 billion last year – including US$206.8 million for hypersonic defence programmes."
Going with a bigger spread just because I don’t know anything about this question but betting heavy on 3 seems irrational with a year yet to go
Going down from 100% for 3. Haven’t seen anything solidly supporting so many tests in a year. Confirmation does appear to lag event, however.

Successful test in March 2020 makes production of new C-HGB missiles faster. Hypersonic missiles (Mach-5 or faster) are at the forefront of the new superpower arms race. The U.S. Army, Navy & Air Force want launching capabilities between 2022-2024. Army and Navy plans to conduct 3 flight tests in 2021... "ambitious" Lockheed Martin; 9-figure government contract on mobile launcher Developing the C-HGB as a base for offensive hypersonic missiles. Typically takes multiple months before the U.S. officially acknowledges missile testing. RESULT Outcome 0: 1% Outcome 1: 13% Outcome 2: 47% Outcome 3: 36% Outcome 4 or more: 3%
Gjo has confirmed a successful joint exercise will resolve as a yes.
Australia is going to be helping - https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/australia-to-begin-testing-hypersonic-missiles-within-months-20201130-p56j5a.html

Increasing confidence in 3 (following the crowd a bit). Leaving 15% at 1 in case double test gets delayed (it's near the end of the question period). Leaving 10% at 2 in case one of the glide bodies is unsuccessful.
Why am I in this question?

an estimate of three min - one fore each services model, but I think ,maybe 4 to allow for a Navy Boost Rocket variant test (Possibly Sub Launched.). https://news.usni.org/2020/11/11/report-on-u-s-hypersonic-weapon-development-3?utm_source=USNI+News&utm_campaign=599d2b4ca7-USNI_NEWS_DAILY&utm_medium=email&utm_term=0_0dd4a1450b-599d2b4ca7-231045397&mc_cid=599d2b4ca7&mc_eid=2394c94b5b
Skewing a bit more toward all three on time and successful, but leaving some room in the event the double test near the end of the timeframe gets pushed back or one or two of the glide bodies fail.

A test with two C-HGBs counts as two, so that puts it at 3 attempts in 2021. I think it's most likely they're all successful. Leaving some on 2 and 1 in the event that the second test gets delayed to 2022 and on chances of test failures. Small chance of 4 in the event of a schedule change, but seems unlikely since the current schedule appears to already be described as aggressive.

I reached out to the author of the Defense News articles regarding the contradictory number of tests being mentioned and she said she believes one of the tests will involve two missiles which is why different numbers were being given. I contacted the moderators about this to see what they say, but I'm guessing that it would still count as one test. Which in that case would mean 2 tests scheduled in the timeframe, and I'm leaning toward it being most likely that both tests happen on schedule and succeed.

There seems to be some contradictory information floating around. In an interview from August General Thurgood says one test in mid 2021 and two tests in later 2021. In a defense news article from October referencing an interview with Thurgood from before the AUSA conference (which took place in October) they say a test in Q3 of FY 2021, a test in Q1 of FY 2022, and two tests in Q3 of FY 2022.

Defense News reported in August that DoD plans to accelerate the C-HGB program by having a flight test in the middle of 2021, and two more later in the year, with weapon deployment in 2023. This accelerated effort is accompanied by a $2.9 billion budget for 2021 [2].

There is this Defense News article sting that the military plans to do 3 testshttps://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/smd/2020/08/05/heres-how-the-dod-plans-to-meet-its-ambitious-hypersonic-missile-test-schedule/

Lots of article citations of the 3 launches in 2021. If we take that at face value, we need to assume some chance that they won't be successful. In addition, we need to assume there's a good chance that 3 tests is their "minimum" number in 2021.
It seems likely there will be some movement on this program in 2021, with at least one flight. Unless something unexpected happens, I lean towards more flights later in the year.
My mistake https://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/smd/2020/08/05/heres-how-the-dod-plans-to-meet-its-ambitious-hypersonic-missile-test-schedule/
@mchivis is correct. All articles seem to point to 1 test in later 2021... I wonder if Trump’s moniker of “super duper missile” will stick!

Breaking Defense announced the next test is scheduled for the 3rd quarter of '21 and additional flights in the first quarter '22. This means there is one attempt scheduled during this question. 3 of the last four test were successful, and success rates get better

The FY21 budget has increased from $2.6B to $3.2B allowing for a schedule of three planned tests. Although tech planning and results are hugely important in a plan like this, money is the largest driver of expensive testing. A slight probability exists for more than 3 planned tests if the tests either fail or are hugely successful spurring more innovation.
The DOD plan is 3 in this time period. Such plans often suffer delay

They are clearly moving toward this direction - and once they start launching and testing there will be multiple launches. There is a small chance that they come up with a new designation, or this is just a skipping stone technology, in which case they will be testing something else.
I predict there will be a minimum of three tests or more, depending on how those initial three tests go. It is a matter of keeping up with China and Russia and nobody knows who’s in the lead.
